                    <item>
              <title>Keynote: Clay The future of learning</title>
              <link>https://cloudworks.ac.uk/cloud/view/2771</link>
              <guid>https://cloudworks.ac.uk/cloud/view/2771</guid>
              <description><![CDATA[<p><strong>James Clay The future of learning</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>Please turn on your mobiles and anything else&hellip;</li>
<li>Books important &ndash; its about giving learners choice</li>
<li>James plans to talk about mbile learning</li>
<li>Is mobile learning about using mobile device, is it learning on the move, or mobility of the learenr</li>
<li>why do we have mobile devices and why more than one?</li>
<li>Iphone only 2 years old from a phone to something that you can communicate and collaborate in a wealth of ways, changed the way we do it</li>
<li>PSP allows you to watch video, listen to audio, watch images, wifi, got a browser, can be a content creator</li>
<li>Often with technologies can have unintended consequences</li>
<li>Learners can appropriate their devices for their needs</li>
<li>Why arent universities braintraining?</li>
<li>You dont get web 2.0 stuff unless you do it</li>
<li>Starting to see with young kids that they are appropriating technologies with ease</li>
<li>Web technologies makes it easier to engae learners in a variety of ways</li>
<li>Service such as Qik turns your mobile device into a TV device</li>
<li>Not about banning the technologies its about educating the users</li>
<li>Twitter is transformative, twitter is about the coffee... coffee conversations</li>
<li>With new technologies comes new responsibilities </li>
<li>We can learn so much more by working across sector boundaries</li>
<li>Learners can access their infomration where and when they want to, they can choose where and when they want to learn</li>
<li>Blurrs the boundaries between formal and informal learning</li>
<li>Concept of visitors and residents in the digital landscape</li>
<li>Benefits of time, personalisaton, reflection</li>
<li>We need to develop new ways of working</li>
</ul>
<p>What are the disadvantages of mobile learning?</p>
<ul>
<li>Technological barriers</li>
<li>Costs (of devices and connectivity)</li>
<li>Theft as an issue</li>
<li>Resistance</li>
<li>Data charges</li>
<li>Innovation Prevention Department</li>
</ul>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<ul>
<li>Choice - we all have different personal preferences. It's the context that's importnat. Raido, TV, theatre, internet etc all site side by side....</li>
<li>The world is changing but are our institutions changing?</li>
<li>We start college in September because our students need to get the harverst in ;-)</li>
<li>We need to adopt a more holistic approach, we need to be responsive to the needs of learners, think about the activities students do and we need to think about flexibility, we need to start charing and collaboratiing.</li>
<li>Stop thinking about barriers and think about solutions, need to change our culture</li>
<li>The future of learning needs to be in the hands of learners</li>
</ul>]]></description>
          <pubDate>Wed, 09 Dec 2009 00:45:32 +0000</pubDate>
            </item>
                    <item>
              <title>Presentation: Goodyear, Kali &amp; Tickner Complex spaces for learning: theory and practice in design, co-design and re-design</title>
              <link>https://cloudworks.ac.uk/cloud/view/2762</link>
              <guid>https://cloudworks.ac.uk/cloud/view/2762</guid>
              <description><![CDATA[<p><strong>Complex spaces for learning: theory and practice in design, co-design and re-design</strong></p>
<p><em>Peter Goodyear, Yael Kali and Sue Tickner</em></p>
<p>Plan is to produce a report out of the event, want people to feel free to be frank.</p>
<p><em>Peter Goodyear</em></p>
<p>A central challenge that emerges from the changing landscape is about working out how we can make pedagogical sense of these changes. Can we view design as a means of managing this change, what would this look like? Spaces for learning &ndash; physical, virtual are becoming more complex. Couple that with a notion that students will and should be more actively involved in reconfiguring their own learning.</p>
<ul>
<li>Experience of co-design with students and also re-design</li>
<li>Design as imaging other people&rsquo;s learning</li>
<li>Activity distributed in complex ways across time, space, tools and people</li>
<li>Students and teacher co-configuring activity relationships and learnplaces</li>
<li>Extended concept of self-regulation: activity relationships and tools/resources</li>
</ul>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>Lassez-faire&hellip;&hellip;&hellip;&hellip;&hellip;Instructional design</p>
<p>[loose vs. tight structures]</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>Not just about managing activities but the social interactions., also how to make good choices about tools and resources.</p>
<p>Is design too complicated &ndash; should we just let students get on with it??? Some argue from the position of students as experts anyway, aligning with Prensky&rsquo;s notions, whereas now most don&rsquo;t subscribe to that position. In reality students&rsquo; digital habits are very varied, they may not know how to use these technologies for learning</p>
<p>Alternative approach to help students find their way through this space, need classic application of instructional design and more rigour, discipline, etc.</p>
<p>In reality it&rsquo;s probably somewhere in between.</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p><strong>Teaching as design</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>Diversifying student needs and expectations</li>
<li>Rising expectations abut graduate capabilities</li>
<li>Intensification of pressures on teaching staff</li>
<li>Accelerating technological change</li>
</ul>
<p>Increasing stress on traditional teaching processes</p>
<p>Accumulating research evidence about learning and teaching</p>
<p>Activity-centred design &ndash; design cannot be content focussed, must be on what the student does. It&rsquo;s the alignment between the desired learning outcomes and the activities we want the students to engage with. A key element of the design challenge is designing the student tasks. Of course students will interpret what we ask them to do (for good or bad). There is a gap between the tasks we set and the activities the students do.</p>
<p>We must remember that learning is physically situated &ndash; there are multiple learnplaces and this is fundamentally important and shapes the quality of the activities the students do.</p>
<p>Also learning is socially situated, groups, teams and communities + virtual teams, groups, and communities</p>
<p>Accelerating interpenetration of the digital and material worlds</p>
<p>Ubiquitous computing/ambient intelligence</p>
<p>Rise and rise of personal technologies</p>
<p><strong>Three inter-related components</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>Outcomes</li>
<li>Activity &ndash; place is a part of this, as is community. We must remember we don&rsquo;t control these spaces </li>
<li>Task</li>
</ul>
<p>We also need to think about scale &ndash; macro, meso and micro. For each we can think about tasks, tools and people. A lot of what we do as teachers is at the meso level. Design of a single task, mapped to a single coherent activity. Timeframe days or weeks. The set of tools, spaces and other resource needed for the learners works on a specific activity. Usually the concern of a teacher or programme team, may be co-configured by the learner(s). People: arrangement into working groups that persist for the length of the activity.</p>
<p>Teaching as design is indirect because of</p>
<ul>
<li>The legitimate and unavoidable gap between tasks and activity</li>
<li>Co-configuration of the complex mix</li>
<li>Autonomy exercised by students in making choice about who to work with and how but needs careful scaffolding</li>
<li>Plus alignment up and down the system macro &ndash; to micro-</li>
<li>Against this can we support teachers design work?</li>
</ul>
<p><em>Sue Tickner</em></p>
<p>Imaging learning: enabling design</p>
<p>Design/learning</p>
<p>Action (Revised design) &ndash; feedback &ndash; opportunity to respond (feed forward)</p>
<p>Dialogic process to reach a mutual understanding &ndash; when design is collaborative there are more opportunities for feedback and so learning</p>
<p>Levels of collaborative design?</p>
<ol>
<li>Reacting to feedback on existing design &ndash; adaptive</li>
<li>Designing for student contributions to and flexible use of environment we provide tools and resources and opportunities</li>
<li>Handing over (parts of) the design to the learners</li>
</ol>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<ol>
<li>On the fly, rapid changes according to feedback. In the moment imaging the immediate learning needs, they need new space for this, just in time, highly responsive contextual, at extreme, similar to formative testing, rapid prototyping, labs observation, on going support. Examples &ndash; one-click surveys within a course, watching their intros in labs, group discussions need to come back together, add a new whole class one. Also process &ndash; design stems from philosophy and values, reflected in methods, the &lsquo;teachable moment&rsquo;</li>
<li>Negotiated marking criteria/assessment rubrics. Co-constructed bibliographies and resource banks. Evaluation criteria for group processes. Spaces for students to create/share their own resources. Examples role play scenarios, resource bank wiki. Educ 230 Wikis, blogs, negotiated assessment criteria, self-assessment, group process critique. Self and peer assessment, criteria and review. Orientation course &ndash; chat, RSS feeds, practice wikis. Self, group, lecturer-reflection. As locus of control shifts during the shared assessment process, there is also a greater appreciation that all learners are teachers and teachers continue to be learners.</li>
<li>Students co-construct teaching resources in groups using whatever of the available technologies/resources they choose. Then create teaching spaces and co-teach. Students create resource banks and presentations to share. TLT group smart classrooms. Communication and making connections, sharing resources, encourage learners to interact spontaneously. Wheatley and Frieze *2006 using emergence to take social innovation to scale </li>
</ol>
<p><em>Yael Kali</em></p>
<p><strong>Redesign as a strategy to create, refine and share design knowledge gained in an iterative design process</strong></p>
<p>Approach to design &ndash; methodological approach &ndash; design-based research and strategic approach the use of the design principles and the design principles database (DPD)</p>
<p>Methodological approach &ndash; Barab and Squire 2004, Collins, Joseph and Bielaczyc 2004, The design-based research collective 2003</p>
<ul>
<li>Iteration 1</li>
<li>Iteration 2 Enactment of the revised version of the features, data gathering, data analysis and conclusions</li>
<li>Iteration 3</li>
</ul>
<p>Design Principles Database</p>
<p>Edu-design-principles.org Create an infrastructure for the community of educational technology designers and learning scientists to capture synthesise and discuss design knowledge</p>
<p>Structure is hierarchical have over 100 examples. Features then pragmatic principles (general guidelines about design, but also connected to learning theory) and then meta-principles</p>
<p>Example: web-based jigsaw activity: philosophical perspectives</p>
<p>Specialization groups in online discussions (progressivism, existentialism, essentialism), the knowledge sharing in home groups, then individual application of the knowledge in a new context (using perspective to analyse a school)</p>
<p>DP1: engage learners in peer instruction. Rationale &ndash; taking the role of instructor can encourage sutdents to depend understaning of content, increase motivation etc Topping 1996 Linn and His 2000 But trade off main contribution to those who instruct and less to those who learn</p>
<p>DP2: reuse students artefacts as resource for further learning</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>Iteration 1 &ndash; First version was unstructured discussion, found very low application of the knowledge in a new context, Students focussed on the perspective they had specialised in.</p>
<p>Iteration 2: Provided them with a tool. Collaboratively constructed table as attachment in the forum. Found application of knowledge was even lower!!!</p>
<p>Iteration 3: Used the same table, but this time students didn&rsquo;t download, it was in a wiki format. This made a big difference, because when they completed their rows they could see what others had contributed and could compare and contrast. Also enabled them to edit each others&rsquo; contributions. So a better application of DP3 and DP4</p>
<p>DP3: provide knowledge representation and organisation tools</p>
<p>DP4: Employ multiple social activity structures</p>
<p>Lessons learned &ndash; redesign as a strategy to create, refine and share design knowledge gained in an iterative design process. Design based research approach provides insights about the use of technology to apply design principles</p>
<p>Design knowledge gained in this process can become part of the design principles (tips: tradeoffs, pitfalls, limitations)</p>
<p>Comments on the presentation</p>
<ul>
<li>Small tweaks in redesign can have a huge impact on the success of the activity.</li>
<li>Interesting that between iteration 2 and 3 the major change was in the tool rather than the tasks.</li>
</ul>
<ul>
<li>Learners can be initially quite reluctant to edit their co-learners contributions, need to encourage and support that</li>
</ul>
<p><strong>Discussion</strong></p>
<p>What do you do when people don&rsquo;t agree about the edits in the wiki, one delegate has a forum alongside the wiki so there can be a negotiation about how the wiki is edited</p>
<p><em>Issues </em></p>
<p>Co-design: Think about situations where you have handed over to the students, so there is considerable autonomy given over to the students. Think around tasks, tools, or how they work with others. Wants us to concentrate on the latter two rather than tasks.</p>
<p>Examples</p>
<ul>
<li>One example with masters&rsquo; students. Give flexibility to choose their research questions and focus and which databases to use, but they wanted to be guided more.</li>
<li>Cancelled all lectures once and told students to go and look at the materials online.</li>
<li>Students working in a global context and had to negotiate a project. They all abandoned the learner management space and took their discussion to a private space.</li>
<li>P/g e-learning course, last year moved to more flexible approach, allowed them to take over certain parts of the course and they choose the tools they wanted to use and moderated the space.</li>
<li>Put students into a public social networking site and asked them to share they professional practice and some interesting debates occurred in the communities.</li>
<li>Another example got the students to write a chapter around their subject area.</li>
</ul>
<p>Re-design: Has anyone got examples they can share of good re-designs? It's not just about re-designs which are based on solid data but also scholarly practice - teachers often have a natural, intuitive understanding of what works and what doesn't. Iterative re-design is surely an inherent part of teacher practice.</p>]]></description>
          <pubDate>Tue, 08 Dec 2009 01:40:05 +0000</pubDate>
            </item>
                    <item>
              <title>Presentation: Nicol </title>
              <link>https://cloudworks.ac.uk/cloud/view/2756</link>
              <guid>https://cloudworks.ac.uk/cloud/view/2756</guid>
              <description><![CDATA[<p>Mark Nicols &ndash; Invited Speaker</p>
<ul>
<li>New way of thinking about e-learning, challenge the assumptions we make, expose the things we take for granted.</li>
<li>No powerpoint, no slideshare, no handouts &ndash; just have to concentrate on what I am talking about</li>
</ul>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p><strong>Focus of the talk is on the dangers of group thinking</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>Marc Prenskys work &ndash; digital natives and immigrants, cited over 15000 times!</li>
<li>Disproves a tenant of web 2.0 wisdom of the crowd &ndash; can be dangerously wrong. The combine opinion is more valuable than the expertise of one. Connect to others</li>
<li>Prensky was wrong and we as the wisdom of the crowds bought it</li>
<li>We need to ask serious questions for what we are taking for granted &ndash; we are suckers for bright lights, free and easy learners</li>
<li>Prensky became true because we all thought it was true</li>
<li>There are so many sources of information we tend to take shortcuts, we go with our comfort zone, our paradigm</li>
<li>Many of our shared values as e-learning researchers may well be wrong &ndash; we never serious challenge our beliefs, our online connectivity only exacerbate this problem Clay Shirky &ndash; we tend to link with people who are just like us</li>
<li>The narrowing of opinions &ndash; web 2.0 narrows our thinking</li>
<li>We cling to ideas and maxums without ever challenging them, we choose who we listen to and also who we don&rsquo;t listen</li>
<li>Those who question the value of e-learning are not here.</li>
<li>We uncritically accept evidence that agrees with our beliefs</li>
<li>We don&rsquo;t adequately read anymore, we read the exec summary and assume we have what the whole report is about. We don&rsquo;t look at the deeper context.</li>
<li>Evaluation of evidence-based online learning report, from US came out earlier this year. Based on in-depth analysis. Exec summary online learning better than face to face blended is better again. But more deep reading is contrary to this, very little difference. Actually the difference appears to be more to do with the fact that online courses require students to spend more time on task than the technological dimension. Latest report from educause also indicates that faculty need to work harder online as well.</li>
<li>Little evidence that e-learning is better at the meta-level, reality is that students and faculty have to work harder, have higher drop out and is expensive.</li>
<li>A lot of the rhetoric of e-learning is little more than a dream.</li>
<li>Public libraries have been available for centuries but in reality students go to universities.&nbsp; So what&rsquo;s new?</li>
<li>Laurillard</li>
<li>Everyday knowledge is based on experience, serve our immediate needs</li>
<li>Academic knowledge is different, more complex &ndash; relating to descriptions of the world, its about paradigm construction and criticisms. Its knowledge about everyday knowledge, its based on our reflection of everyday knowledge and the search for hard evidence, serve society needs</li>
<li>This distinction is essential, universities are about dealing with academic knowledge</li>
<li>&nbsp;We need to beware of group thinking, we need to be more critically aware of our area and the wisdom of the crowds discourse associated with it.</li>
</ul>]]></description>
