                    <item>
              <title>Keynote: Doug Johnson</title>
              <link>https://cloudworks.ac.uk/cloud/view/2563</link>
              <guid>https://cloudworks.ac.uk/cloud/view/2563</guid>
              <description><![CDATA[<p><strong>Schools for the Net Generation</strong></p>
<p>Doug talked about the Net Generation drawing on a range of studies. His focus was on the implications for schools and for how we teach.</p>
<p><em>Net Generation - learning styles</em></p>
<p>Teachers are still vital - computers can't replace humans</p>
<p>Social learners</p>
<p>Seek personal information</p>
<p>Remixed 0 share, 57 % content creators</p>
<p>Learning styles - mind shaped by technology and media (hypertext minds, read visual images, inductive discovery, learn by doing, shift attention rapidly - tune out of things not of interest, need encouragemnet to reflect, expect fast responses)</p>
<p><strong>From entertain to engage</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>Purpose: enjoyment - learning</li>
<li>Impact: ephemeral - permanent</li>
<li>Relevance: little or non &ndash; high</li>
<li>Problems: escape - solving</li>
<li>Creativity: shown by others &ndash; shown by the learner</li>
<li>Activity: passive - interactive</li>
</ul>
<p>This generation are more interactive, they are contet producers</p>
<p><strong>Implications</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>Relevance</li>
<li>Use, not ban, web 2.0 tools</li>
<li>Teach and use collaborative groups</li>
<li>Teach copyrights from point of view of the creator</li>
<li>Emphasis on safe and ethical use</li>
</ul>
<p><strong>Values</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>Acheivement oriented - cool to be smart, focused on grades, rules, schedules and agendas</li>
<li>work on things tht matter</li>
<li>Identify on parent vlaues</li>
<li>Busy with extra activities</li>
<li>Unaware of the consequences o their tech use - 75% agree - downloading and file sharing is so easy to do, its unrealistic to espect people not to do it</li>
<li>This generation is "differently moral"</li>
</ul>
<p>Need to teach the kids how to protect themselves, from themselves as well as others</p>]]></description>
