            </item>
                    <item>
              <title>Home group 3: The Icelandic Cloud</title>
              <link>https://cloudworks.ac.uk/cloud/view/2343</link>
              <guid>https://cloudworks.ac.uk/cloud/view/2343</guid>
              <description><![CDATA[<p>This cloud summarises the discussions of the &ldquo;home group&rdquo; called &ldquo;the icelandic cloud&rdquo; at the Cambridge International Conference of Open and Distance Learning. The full cloudscape for the conference is available <a href="/cloudscape/view/1890">here</a>. The aim of the home groups is to enable participants to discuss in more depth issues that arise out of the keynote presentations.</p>
<p><em>Discussions after <a href="/cloud/view/2338">Sugata Mitra&rsquo;s keynote</a></em></p>
<p>One of the central discussion points of the group was around the issue of what is the role of face-to-face teaching versus online. Sugata&rsquo;s three characteristics particularly struck a cord with the group, in terms of factors to foster/support learning:</p>
<ul>
<li>Providing a safe place/environment for learning</li>
<li>Associate with play</li>
<li>Ensure that it is a non-structured environment</li>
</ul>
<p>We wondered how these factors could be applied in an adult learning context? One of the participants told us he had been an online tutor for 12 years and that he felt he know much more about his online students than face-to-face ones because of the level of interaction and dialogue.</p>
<p>The quality of the construction of the learning process online was raised as an issue &ndash; how should such spaces be constructed and supported?</p>
<p>There were different views in the group however in terms of the degree to which student actually want to collaborate and work with others. In particular, students who are in a work-based context often just want to focus on what it is that they need to do to get through and pass and they actively don&rsquo;t want to work with others. [Interesting this tied in nicely with Morton&rsquo;s statistics from his university where only 36% of students choose to take up the option of having a learning partner.</p>
<p>The group also discussed what were the different factors, which make an online learning context successful &ndash; such as the size of the group, the degree of moderation, the amount of structuring. Gender issues were also raised as an issue.</p>
<p><em>Discussions after <a href="/cloud/view/2340">Morton Paulsen&rsquo;s keynote</a></em></p>
<p>If students are all self-paced, how does the assessment actually work? What is the ratio of students to tutors? Maybe the solution is to have individualised, unique assignments. The partnership model and the flexible pacing are key features and will influence the design of the courses, activities and assignments. Partnership mode will foster better learning, through dialogue with another. Interesting that most of the students opted to work individually rather than with others. What was really striking was the amount of student control.</p>
<p>Many students learn very well in a structured, group project. &nbsp;Sometimes we have to realise that group learning is good for students even if they don&rsquo;t want to do it! Enables divergent rather than convergent learning and understanding. It&rsquo;s a challenge and there is an issue in terms of the balance.</p>
<p>In the Open University, New Zealand a lot of students get their own learning partners via the workplace. It was interesting in Paulen&rsquo;s statistic to see that only 36% of students wanted a learning partner. Is there a difference if you are at the beginning of your study or the opposite ie once you have more confidence you are willing to work with others. Likewise there are likely to be discipline differences, for example are Arts-based students more likely to want to work together and discuss than Science-based students? Also is there a gender difference?</p>
<p>We wondered what kind of tools the students studying with NKI have to support the learning partnerships?</p>
<p>The more freedom you give to the students, the more important the planning and structuring needs to be. Needs a complex, well balanced system to support this.</p>
<p>Asby&rsquo;s law &ndash; the more complex the situation, the more complex the structure needs to be. <a href="http://pespmc1.vub.ac.be/REQVAR.HTML">http://pespmc1.vub.ac.be/REQVAR.HTML</a> The law of requisite variety</p>
<p>Motivation &ndash; how are the students motivated when they are working on their own.</p>
<p>Importance of continual encouragement via letters and emails &ndash; has a direct impact on retention.</p>
<p>One of the issues for institutions with a large number of modules is how do you coordinate it &ndash; for example ensuring you don&rsquo;t have all the assignment deadlines at the same time.</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>]]></description>
          <pubDate>Wed, 23 Sep 2009 10:18:39 +0000</pubDate>
            </item>
                    <item>
              <title>Keynote: Paulsen - Visualizing student profiles through NKI’s online catalogue and student network</title>
              <link>https://cloudworks.ac.uk/cloud/view/2340</link>
              <guid>https://cloudworks.ac.uk/cloud/view/2340</guid>
              <description><![CDATA[<p>Will live blog Morten's keynote here...</p>
<p>NKI is a non-state distance institution in Norway</p>
<p>Key focus for Morten is: How can we make online students more visible?</p>
<p><em>Background</em></p>
<ul>
<li>NKI Distance Education &ndash; one of Europe largest provides of online distance education, more than 110,000 enrolments since 1987</li>
<li>Broad range of subjects</li>
<li>About 400 courses, ca. 11,000 students in ca. 40 countries, ca. 70% women</li>
<li>Only self paced courses, start whenever they want, individual progress plans</li>
<li>Have a mixture of online and correspondence students</li>
<li>Cooperative online education allows students a lot of individual flexibility &ndash; can start and finish when they want but also access to a learning community &ndash; difficult to balance these two things &ndash; cooperative learning: learning in networks, similar to what we see in social networking</li>
</ul>
<p><em>Philosophy</em></p>
<ul>
<li>Individual freedom within a learning community in which online students serve as mutual resource without being dependent on each other.</li>
<li>Support individual freedom &ndash; can start whenever they like, they have tools to develop their individual progress plans, automatic tracking of turnaround time.</li>
<li>Also have tools to support learning communities, forum etc. Also a learning partner system so they can find a study buddy to work with and a global catalogue</li>
</ul>
<p>A lot of innovations at NKI &ndash; started in 1986 &ndash; first Learning Management System through to individual learning system, continuous tracking and turnaround, learning partner system</p>
<p>Continuous turn around &ndash; average time is 2 days. Introduced in 2004, resulted in much discussion in the teachers&rsquo; online forum and a few voiced strong criticisms. But the average response rate dropped as a result of the introduction of the system. In 2008 introduced automatic e-mail reminded to tutors.</p>
<p><em>Individual planning system as voluntary option in 2004</em></p>
<ul>
<li>Makes it easier for student to reach their study goals, students can see individual progress and so can the tutors</li>
<li>In January 2009 started to email individual monthly progress reports to all students&nbsp; - contains contact information, LMS settings, progress report and planned progress. Intention is to send a personal, positive statement to every student, every month.</li>
<li>Have lists with information about next submission umber and planned submission dates make cooperation easier.</li>
</ul>
<p><em>Boldic award 2006 &ndash; NKI&rsquo;s learning partner</em></p>
<ul>
<li>Innovative service for voluntary cooperation between students in a large online community.</li>
<li>Inspired by facebook, linked in etc</li>
<li>Consists of 4 steps. Make your personal presentation, decide who may access it, search for potential learning partners and invite someone to become your learning partner.</li>
</ul>
<p><em>Global presentation</em></p>
<p>Their presentation has details about when they started, if they have learning partners, list of the courses they have enrolled on, etc. Encourage them to enter some more personal information about themselves, picture, interests, previous educational and work experience etc. They can choose whether or not to have a profile and the extent to which it is open or closed. 36% want a learning partner and 64% don&rsquo;t. Default is limited visibility and don&rsquo;t want a learning partner. Quite a number of the students prefer to work alone.</p>
<p>Google translation of global catalogue: http://<a href="http://www.nki.no/pp">www.nki.no/pp</a></p>
<p>Presentations show that online courses support individual needs and challenges &ndash; some key phrases from their presentations</p>
<p>&ldquo;I need flexibility to study&rdquo;</p>
<ul>
<li>A lot of student with young children: &ldquo;When I got pregnant I found that it was easier to finish school via online courses&rdquo;</li>
<li>A range of learning challenges and illnesses: &ldquo;I have dyslexia&rdquo; &ldquo;I&rsquo;ve been diagnosed with multiple sclerosis&rdquo;</li>
</ul>
<p>Benefits: like opportunity to share their experiences with other students, friends and family. Valuable also for the field of distance education. Distance students can tend to be quite invisible, this helps to make them more visible. Great ambassadors for NKI and information for new students, trustworthy testimonials. Presentations have resulted in more co-operations as they know each other better. Students also now know more about their students.</p>
<p><em>Transparency or privacy?<br /></em></p>
<p>What kind of information should be available? Transparency or privacy? Paulsen leans more towards transparency.</p>
<p>Risks: inappropriate content, copyright issues, criticisms from dissatisfied students, student who explore too much personal information. But on the whole have had few issues and problems. Paulsen believed transparency improves quality, error correction, preventive quality, learning quality. Also it promotes cooperation.</p>]]></description>
          <pubDate>Wed, 23 Sep 2009 07:53:04 +0000</pubDate>
            </item>
                    <item>
              <title>Keynote: Mitra - Towards the future of learning</title>
              <link>https://cloudworks.ac.uk/cloud/view/2338</link>
              <guid>https://cloudworks.ac.uk/cloud/view/2338</guid>
              <description><![CDATA[<p><strong>The antithesis experiment &ndash; towards a curriculum, pedagogy and technology for self regulated school education</strong></p>
<p><em>Sugata Mitra, University of Newcastle</em></p>
<p>Sugata outlined some of his work over the past decade or so and his vision of&nbsp; new education for children&hellip;</p>
<p>These are some live blogging notes from his keynote.</p>
<ul>
<li>There will always be people in the world who are willing to mediate in children&rsquo;s learning for say an hour a week with no remuneration. Therefore if we create clouds of mediators and children on the internet and an arrangement by which they can interact, potentially then we would have an alternative schooling.</li>
</ul>
<ul>
<li>In past three years Sugata and his team have created 12 Self Organised Learning Environments (SOLEs) in addition to the several hundred &lsquo;hole in the wall&rsquo; computers that exist in India, Cambodia and several African countries. There exists a cloud of mediators that have begun to interact with these SOLEs. The cloud is self-organised and called a Self Organised Mediation Environment (SOME). The mediator interact with the children over Skpe.</li>
</ul>
<p>For a paper describing this work in more detail, refer to (also linked above):&nbsp; <a href="http://www.academypublisher.com/jetwi/vol1/no1/jetwi01015559.pdf">http://www.academypublisher.com/jetwi/vol1/no1/jetwi01015559.pdf</a></p>
<p>He decided recently to come up with a new, bolder title for this keynote...</p>
<p><strong>New title for the talk: The future of learning</strong></p>
<p><em>Learning in the past</em></p>
<ul>
<li>1983 (around the start of the Int. Cambridge Conference) was 26 years ago, can we say that 26 years from now will be at least as different as 26 years ago/ So what was it like in 1983?&nbsp; IBM PC doesn&rsquo;t exist, windows doesn&rsquo;t exist, networking is an idea in labs, the internet doesn&rsquo;t exist. Computers in schools consisted of screens of text with children&rsquo;s answers questions &ndash; BBC micros, but little learning evident. Going back further to images of Victorian learning in the UK, presents an image of: no girls, aging male teacher (with a stick), with a blackboard, sadly you can still&nbsp; find examples of this in some parts of the world today. More generally, nowadays the blackboard has been replaced by a whiteboard and a smartboard, the teacher is typically a young women. What are the changes and where are we heading?</li>
</ul>
<p><em>The origins of the hole in the wall experiment</em></p>
<ul>
<li>The hole in the wall experiment is now 10 years old. 1999 urban India big issue is the digital divide. What about poor children in rural India? Computer teachers are now necessarily good at computing! Ie if they are good they will go into industry. Government trained them, all the good ones leave and go into industries, the bad ones go into cities, the really bad ones go into rural areas &ndash; where they say computers are expensive and not for children. Hence the idea of the hole in the wall to bring computers to children &ndash; windows plus Internet, in a slum area. Assumed that it would be broken/stolen. Didn&rsquo;t happen, saw two children one showing the other how to browse. Passers by might have helped. Even with no one there to help they worked out how to use it, download, browse etc. The kids engaged with it and worked it out.&nbsp; Repeated the experiment &ndash; found kids learnt English so they could use the computer, adults would say you gave us a computer in a language I don&rsquo;t understand so I cant use it, whereas the kids learn how to and are more resourceful.</li>
</ul>
<ul>
<li>The first phase lasted about five years. Conclusions: </li>
</ul>
<blockquote><ol>
<li>groups of children can learn to use computers on their own irrespective of where they are (in India, Cambodia, 7 African countries, UK and Norway),</li>
<li>After 9 months &ndash; basic windows, chat, browse, download, play video, email, games and educational material &ndash; they do it because of adult management and administration, it&rsquo;s a self organising system, share the time, manage themselves, etc. ,</li>
<li>These effects can be achieved if you put the computer in a safe open area where the kids can explore and play on their own, away from adult supervision. It happens because of the absence of adults, </li>
<li>Cost is ca. 3 US cents per child per day &ndash; ca. 30 dollars per child over a three year period leading to an irreversible change.</li>
<li>Also distinct improvement in the kids&rsquo; schoolwork &ndash; English, Maths. Also a change in social values, improvement in school attendance, reduces school drop out rate and reduces petty crime. Generates local goodwill. </li>
</ol></blockquote>
<ul>
</ul>
<ul>
<li>The Hyderabad experiment 2002: &ldquo;given the appropriate digital resources groups of kids can improve their English pronunciation by themselves&rdquo;. Poor city in Southern India with lots of small private schools trying to teach English. Teachers have a Southern Indian accent and so learn English with this. Used a speak to text engine, train the machine in your language and then you can dictate it and repeat it back and adapted the programme so that the kids could do this on their own, process of trial and error.</li>
</ul>
<ul>
<li>The BBC experiement in Varna in 2005. A village of kids who sing, and somehow they found the recording facility in windows and were able to record themselves. Phase2 can self organise to teach themselves, improve their skills and english, they don&rsquo;t need instruction.</li>
</ul>
<p><em>What happens next? </em></p>
<p>Sugata has been at Newcastle for three years now. If this is all true, what is there that children cant learn on their own. Can Tamil speaking kids learn biotechnology in English on their own. Put hole in the wall in Kuppam in 2007, which was hit by the 2004 Asian Tsunami. Downloaded material on biotechnology and DNA replication.&nbsp; Came back after two months &ndash; 22 kids. Post test &ndash; 30%!!! It happened all because of a 12 year old girl. She phoned an uncle in Bombay &ndash; she asked him the meaning of the word DNA, he explaied&hellip; The real power of peer pressure&hellip; as a method of learning.</p>
<p><em>So now what?</em></p>
<ul>
<li>The Gateshead experiment. All the kids have a laptop. Kids have the laptops but nothing is happening. Tool 32 10 year olds. Divide yourself into groups of 4 and then asked each group to do something. Usually 3 friends and a boffin. Every group of 4 can use only one computer, can talk within the group, switch between groups, look at others groups work and claim it as their won. Gave them 6 GCSE questions, best group did it in 20 minutes, 45 minutes for the worst group, everyone got everything right! Methods &ndash; google, wikipedia, copied answered them. Came back two months later and did the same test. 70% got 70% correct. Why? Think its because of the group of 4, one writes the answer down, others disagree, look at other sources, discuss the different answers etc. Peer collaboration and discussion.</li>
</ul>
<p><em>How far can we go?</em></p>
<ul>
<li>The Longbention project. Group of 60 kids, what do you want to be when you grow up &ndash; foot ballers and fashion designers. The Longbention community project. Watched TED talk on Leonardi de Vinci. Organised into groups of 4. They go on the computer and research what they have just seen. Then made presentations and discussion. After about 8 &ndash; 10 sessions, would their aspirations of what they would like to be. TV only shows basic role models, internet expands their views. In India where there is a bigger divide between rich and poor kids have greater aspirations ironically. In UK where gap not so big they don&rsquo;t want to work that hard, aspire that high.</li>
</ul>
<p><em>Latest work</em></p>
<ul>
<li>Now 13 SO<em>&nbsp;</em>LEs in operations in Hyderabad and Maharashtra. Have game shows with GCSE questions.</li>
</ul>
<ul>
<li>Presence&nbsp; remote presence, Self Organisaed Mediation Environments &ndash; grandmothers who were willing to talk to kids over Skype. Got 200 grandmothers volunteered &ndash; one hour of their time free, most are retired English teachers. Fantastic resource. The teacher is available and kids can ask for help if they need it.</li>
</ul>
<p><em>The future</em></p>
<ul>
<li>Subsidised broadband and electricity in all schools</li>
<li>Self organised fault tolerant technology</li>
<li>Self organised learning environments as part of the timetable</li>
<li>Clouds of mediators as part of faculty</li>
<li>A curriculum that is based on questions which has some meaning (kids ask the question &ndash; why am I doing this?)</li>
<li>A self-organised assessment system</li>
</ul>
<p><em>His vision....what might be possible with a little imagination and vision...<br /></em></p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p style="cursor:auto"><!--NO CSS-->Schools of clouds &ndash; clouds of kids interacting with clouds of mediators driven by questions and a desires to know....</p>
<p style="cursor:auto"><!--NO CSS-->10 million retired teachers &ndash; one hour a week, 10 billion kids&hellip;</p>]]></description>
          <pubDate>Tue, 22 Sep 2009 15:04:06 +0000</pubDate>
