                    <item>
              <title>The reality of the knowledge society</title>
              <link>https://cloudworks.ac.uk/cloud/view/1281</link>
              <guid>https://cloudworks.ac.uk/cloud/view/1281</guid>
              <description><![CDATA[<p>
Angela reflected on some of the rhetoric around the knowledge society. She considered two inter-related aspects:<br />
•    Implications of employability<br />
•    Implications for education? 
</p>
<p>
She drew on work from Voogt and Pelgrum (2005) pedagogy in knowledge-based society.
</p>
<p>
<br />
She argued there is a change from pedagogy in an industrial society to pedagogy in the information society. 
</p>
<ol>
	<li>Active learners (from activities prescribed by teacher to determined by the learner),</li>
	<li>Collaborative (individual to working in teams), </li>
	<li>Creative (reproductive learning to productive learning), </li>
	<li>Integrative (no link bet theory and practice to integrative approach),</li>
	<li>Evaluative (teacher-directed and summative to student-directed and diagnostic)</li>
</ol>
<p>
Potential of digital technologies to support learning show three powerful trends:<br />
1.    Interaction of people and technologies<br />
2.    Production (iteration?)<br />
3.    Feedback and play
</p>
<p>
From some of her research studies Angela summarised the following in terms of kids use of PDAs.
</p>
<p>
<i>High users<br />
</i>
</p>
<ul>
	<li>Relish and enjoy use of the PDA, are proud of owning a PDA</li>
	<li>Are confident and active in developing their skills using the device</li>
	<li>Appreciate the potential of the device and seek to use it</li>
	<li>Explore what the device can do</li>
</ul>
<p>
<i>Low users</i>
</p>
<ul>
	<li>Have basic level of skill and understanding of the PDA,</li>
	<li>Not pro-active, are happy to be dependent on others, </li>
	<li>Have inaccurate perceptions about provision, systems and what the PDA can do, </li>
	<li>Have little exposure to use in the classrom</li>
</ul>
<p>
&nbsp;
</p>
]]></description>
          <pubDate>Mon, 23 Mar 2009 16:02:19 +0000</pubDate>
            </item>
                    <item>
              <title>Dominant discourses in TEL</title>
              <link>https://cloudworks.ac.uk/cloud/view/1279</link>
              <guid>https://cloudworks.ac.uk/cloud/view/1279</guid>
              <description><![CDATA[<ul>
	<li>Radical redesign of education is needed.</li>
	<li>TEL has been around for over 30 years now so why hasn’t it had a more profound impact</li>
</ul>
<p>
The stories we use have an impact on what we do and how we view the world – two dominant narratives – transformation and modernisation
</p>
<ol>
	<li>1.    Transformation – world changing radically, need to capitalise on the potential of technologies – individuals such as Gee, Hepell, Papert – research inspiration – work based, game based, informal learning. But critiques argue that how can we generalise from small/non-scalable examples, values aligned seen as aligned with economics rather than well being, the change everything argument doesn’t help with knowing what to do on Monday, an outsider discourse to education.</li>
	<li>2.    Modernisation. Alternative is the modernisation discourse– Trojan mouse – new technologies powerful, but they can be harnessed, once we have everyone on board then we can look to transformation, educationalists tend to be the leaders of this approach. Critiques argue – it tends not to take account of the new models of education outside the formal context, focus on pedagogy and systems rather than curriculum as such inherently protective of status quo, might be building barriers to more substantial change as it reinforces existing practice.</li>
</ol>
<p>
If we start with a different narrative what would that mean? Expert professional capable of significant reflection, digital natives. Start to see the schools as the drivers of change rather than the recipients of change, so researchers role becomes one of empowerment. Researchers – empowering educators to critique and innovate. Responsive problem solving around specific issues, supporting reflection and knowledge sharing across diff sites.<br />
</p>
]]></description>
          <pubDate>Mon, 23 Mar 2009 15:37:07 +0000</pubDate>
            </item>
                    <item>
              <title>Dan Sutch: Engaging with technological and social changes in education</title>
              <link>https://cloudworks.ac.uk/cloud/view/1274</link>
              <guid>https://cloudworks.ac.uk/cloud/view/1274</guid>
              <description><![CDATA[<p>
Part of <a href="/node/1271">Keri Facer's symposium</a> at CAL 09 on the Beyond current horizon's project. 
</p>
<p>
Looking at public and stakeholder engagement – large list from learners, teachers, parents, policy makers, employers, etc<br />
Importance of agency – multiple actors – ability to act in and on the world within multiple possible futures
</p>
<p>
Wider perspectives and insight – informed participation to increase insight and perspectives within VBCH
</p>
<p>
Futurelab approach – voice, participation, co-design/co-development
</p>
<p>
<br />
Growing engagement agenda – civic participation, active citizenship etc<br />
<br />
<b>Three principles<br />
</b>1.    Deliberative engagement <br />
2.    Normative/typical engagement<br />
3.    Communications/dissemination
</p>
<p>
<b>Approaches used<br />
</b>
</p>
<ol>
	<li>Millionfutures.org.uk , 1539 entries from 100 different counties</li>
	<li>Series of questions about the future, including what are your hopes for the future, what do you want your community to be like, what are your biggest worries – etcPowerleague.org.uk How to educate league, what education for league</li>
	<li>Citizen panel – 10 questions sent to 1100 members of the public, 513 respondents</li>
	<li>Citizen council – senior reps from organisation set up to work for particular groups within society 1. Current values of education, 2. Prioritising emerging evidence from the 5 challenges, 3. Future aims of education.</li>
	<li>Stakeholder workshop and interviews with a wide range of participants</li>
</ol>
<p>
<b>Thinking critically about the future<br />
</b>1.    Questioning assumptions – expectation that things will remain/change<br />
2.    Qualifying conversations of the future with examples from the present<br />
3.    Frames of reference
</p>
<p>
Futures thinking provides an opportunity to be critical of current educational policy/practice<br />
Digital technology in education is still very contested – range of responses, from vital for future of education to concerns of technology overload and dehumanisation of education, emerging technologies were not mentioned at all<br />
A lot of the questions were about the values of education<br />
</p>
